offering.description: IBM WebSphere Application Server Network Deployment is a production-ready Java Platform, Enterprise Edition (Java EE) compliant application server for the deployment of enterprise web services solutions for dynamic e-business. It is the next level in application serving beyond the WebSphere Application Server base edition because it provides advanced web services and clustering capabilities.
offering.name: IBM WebSphere Application Server Network Deployment

feature.description: Before you deploy applications on the server, you must run the EJBDeploy tool on the applications that contain EJB modules. Running the EJBDeploy tool generates deployment code for enterprise beans in the application. Beginning with the EJB 3.0 specification, the EJBDeploy tool is no longer required because WebSphere Application Server uses a new feature called "JITDeploy" which automatically generates code when the application starts; therefore, eliminating the need for the EJBDeploy tool. However, the tool is still available with WebSphere Application Server for applications with modules that are based on specifications prior to EJB 3.0.
feature.name: EJBDeploy tool for pre-EJB 3.0 modules

feature.description: IBM thin clients provide a set of clients for a variety of technologies, such as JAX-WS, JAX-RPC, JAX-RS, XML, EJB, JPA, JMS, and more. IBM resource adapter provides the resource adapter for JMS. See the information center for a complete listing of all thin clients and resource adapters.
feature.name: Stand-alone thin clients and resource adapters

feature.description: The embeddable EJB container is a JAR file that you can use to run enterprise beans in a stand-alone Java Platform, Standard Edition environment. You can run enterprise beans using this embeddable container outside the application server. The embeddable EJB container is a part of the EJB 3.1 specification and is primarily used for unit testing enterprise beans business logic. See the information center for more details about using and configuring the embeddable EJB container.
feature.name: Embeddable EJB container

feature.description: The Samples include both source code files and integrated enterprise applications that demonstrate some of the latest Java (TM) Platform, Enterprise Edition (Java EE) and WebSphere technologies. The samples are recommended for installation to learning and demonstration environments, such as development environments. However, they are not recommended for installation to production application server environments.
feature.name: Sample applications

feature.description: The 64-bit SDK for Java 6 includes the Runtime Environment, which enables you only to run Java applications. When you install the SDK, the Runtime Environment is included. The Runtime Environment contains the Java Virtual Machine and supporting files. The Runtime Environment contains only a subset of the classes that are found in the SDK and allows you to support a Java program at runtime but does not provide compilation of Java programs. The Runtime Environment does not include any of the development tools or classes that are only for development systems.
feature.name: IBM 64-bit WebSphere SDK for Java

offering.description: IBM SDKs provide a full-function Software Development Kit (SDK) for Java, compliant with the Oracle(TM) Java SE 7 application programming interfaces (APIs). With the IBM SDK, Java Technology Edition you can: develop, test and deploy Java applications at the Java 7 API level; and continue the "write once, run anywhere" Java paradigm at the Java API level. The SDK contains the Runtime Environment that allows users to run Java Applications. The SDK also contains additional developer tools that enable developers to create Java Applications.
offering.name: IBM WebSphere SDK Java Technology Edition (Optional)

feature.description: IBM WebSphere SDK for Java Technology Edition 7
feature.name: IBM WebSphere SDK for Java Technology Edition 7
